00:39:35.280 --> 00:39:38.920
I feel like text adventures are
a huge place where innovation

00:39:38.920 --> 00:39:41.900
has happened, But
it's an old thing.

00:39:41.900 --> 00:39:43.530
And I was wondering
if it's something

00:39:43.530 --> 00:39:46.687
that you've looked into
or drawn inspiration from.

00:39:46.687 --> 00:39:48.020
KELLEE SANTIAGO: Oh, definitely.

00:39:48.020 --> 00:39:51.380
I mean, it's been huge,
especially drawing

00:39:51.380 --> 00:39:55.280
in and empowering
the transgender

00:39:55.280 --> 00:39:57.360
community in game development.

00:39:57.360 --> 00:40:03.140
A lot of the Twine
community has really

00:40:03.140 --> 00:40:05.530
empowered that in
such an awesome way.

00:40:05.530 --> 00:40:09.890
So yeah, I think about
how can we build on that.

00:40:09.890 --> 00:40:13.100
Is it just time?

00:40:13.100 --> 00:40:15.680
Is it that tool is
there now and then

00:40:15.680 --> 00:40:19.270
it's just waiting for people
to build up the skill sets?

00:40:19.270 --> 00:40:24.610
Or are those voices getting
lost at a certain point?

00:40:24.610 --> 00:40:26.550
To me, it's what's the
next step from there?

00:40:26.550 --> 00:40:28.832
Because it's definitely
providing a lot of opportunity

00:40:28.832 --> 00:40:30.790
for a lot of people that
didn't have it before.

00:40:33.390 --> 00:40:37.330
And how can I like enable those
experiences in other mediums

00:40:37.330 --> 00:40:39.130
that I'm working on, for sure?

00:40:39.130 --> 00:40:41.522
Some of those, yeah,
they're really great.

00:40:41.522 --> 00:40:43.480
AUDIENCE: I also really
appreciate the call-out

00:40:43.480 --> 00:40:45.190
to the transgender community.

00:40:45.190 --> 00:40:46.389
KELLEE SANTIAGO: Oh sure.

00:40:46.389 --> 00:40:47.430
AUDIENCE: It's important.

00:40:55.060 --> 00:40:58.760
AUDIENCE: So I'm curious,
what makes you decide

00:40:58.760 --> 00:41:00.390
to leave thatgamecompany?

00:41:00.390 --> 00:41:06.045
And what makes you think you
picked VR as the new direction

00:41:06.045 --> 00:41:07.712
to pursue after?

00:41:07.712 --> 00:41:10.030
And do you think
VR is a bad example

00:41:10.030 --> 00:41:12.506
about gaming story like art?

00:41:15.930 --> 00:41:19.070
KELLEE SANTIAGO: Yeah,
so part of the answer

00:41:19.070 --> 00:41:20.730
to thatgamecompany
is easy, which

00:41:20.730 --> 00:41:23.430
is it was six years together.

00:41:23.430 --> 00:41:26.530
And it's like having a company
together is like a long term

00:41:26.530 --> 00:41:27.170
relationship.

00:41:27.170 --> 00:41:30.110
And at that point, either
you're growing together,

00:41:30.110 --> 00:41:33.149
you're all growing and
changing over six years.

00:41:33.149 --> 00:41:35.440
You're either growing together
or you're growing apart,

00:41:35.440 --> 00:41:38.900
and we just recognized
that we were growing apart

00:41:38.900 --> 00:41:41.670
in what we wanted to do next.

00:41:41.670 --> 00:41:47.370
And really, it felt like
putting the round peg

00:41:47.370 --> 00:41:53.640
in the square hole, or vice
versa of being together

00:41:53.640 --> 00:41:55.380
and constraining ourselves.

00:41:55.380 --> 00:41:59.710
So instead, let's separate
and really unchain ourselves

00:41:59.710 --> 00:42:01.990
and feel free to
pursue exactly what it

00:42:01.990 --> 00:42:03.840
is we wanted to be doing.

00:42:03.840 --> 00:42:06.445
One of the things was
originally with thatgamecompany,

00:42:06.445 --> 00:42:08.580
the idea Jenova and
I had was to build

00:42:08.580 --> 00:42:11.230
an umbrella under which
many studios could operate,

00:42:11.230 --> 00:42:14.680
but that's not how
thatgamecompany evolved,

00:42:14.680 --> 00:42:16.940
for good reasons.

00:42:16.940 --> 00:42:18.330
And I still wanted to.

00:42:18.330 --> 00:42:21.760
I still wanted to put
a multiplier effect

00:42:21.760 --> 00:42:23.632
on this impact.

00:42:23.632 --> 00:42:25.090
And that's part of
also what led me

00:42:25.090 --> 00:42:27.830
to Ouya, the
Android-based console

00:42:27.830 --> 00:42:30.170
where I was head of developer
relations and content

00:42:30.170 --> 00:42:32.147
acquisition.

00:42:32.147 --> 00:42:34.480
And it was like the pendulum
swinging all the other way,

00:42:34.480 --> 00:42:38.792
the entire way, where at
thatgamecompany, "Journey" was

00:42:38.792 --> 00:42:39.500
the last project.

00:42:39.500 --> 00:42:43.320
It had been three years,
one game at a time.

00:42:43.320 --> 00:42:48.270
And Ouya was working
on 500 games at a time.

00:42:48.270 --> 00:42:52.150
And now I'm somewhere
in the middle.

00:42:52.150 --> 00:42:55.330
So I got exactly what
I needed out of that

00:42:55.330 --> 00:42:57.710
and continue to do so
at Google in interacting

00:42:57.710 --> 00:43:00.280
with the wide range
of studios and really

00:43:00.280 --> 00:43:07.910
getting to see why things
are the way they are today.

00:43:07.910 --> 00:43:10.495
How do we get to
the places of making

00:43:10.495 --> 00:43:12.870
this certain type of game or
this certain type of product

00:43:12.870 --> 00:43:15.620
and this certain
type of platform.

00:43:15.620 --> 00:43:22.310
As far as why VR and AR, part
of it's because it's new.

00:43:22.310 --> 00:43:28.060
Yet again, the industry is
at this place where there's

00:43:28.060 --> 00:43:32.000
this budding new medium,
and there is very few rules

00:43:32.000 --> 00:43:33.650
and definition around it.

00:43:33.650 --> 00:43:37.770
So here is a time where we
get to play and figure out

00:43:37.770 --> 00:43:38.855
those rules for ourselves.

00:43:41.920 --> 00:43:44.067
yeah?

00:43:44.067 --> 00:43:44.650
AUDIENCE: Hey.

00:43:44.650 --> 00:43:46.020
KELLEE SANTIAGO: Hey.

00:43:46.020 --> 00:43:49.453
AUDIENCE: So with
each of these games,

00:43:49.453 --> 00:43:53.740
the thatgamecompany games,
you had a specific goal,

00:43:53.740 --> 00:43:56.800
an experience you
wanted to evoke.

00:43:56.800 --> 00:43:59.910
But the secondary goal
of almost all games

00:43:59.910 --> 00:44:03.910
is to make it just
a fun experience.

00:44:03.910 --> 00:44:06.980
And you definitely succeeded
on that front as well.

00:44:06.980 --> 00:44:09.200
So I was wondering
if there are times

00:44:09.200 --> 00:44:12.710
when you have to make
compromises between the story

00:44:12.710 --> 00:44:16.320
that you want to tell, the
feeling that you want to evoke,

00:44:16.320 --> 00:44:19.320
and things that
make the game fun?

00:44:19.320 --> 00:44:23.860
Is there any tension there, or
do they just flow naturally?

00:44:23.860 --> 00:44:27.440
KELLEE SANTIAGO: So for me,
I think another word for fun

00:44:27.440 --> 00:44:28.630
is engaging.

00:44:28.630 --> 00:44:34.820
And I think, well,
with some exception,

00:44:34.820 --> 00:44:37.010
there are games
intentionally not fun

00:44:37.010 --> 00:44:39.390
or intentionally not engaging.

00:44:39.390 --> 00:44:41.720
But when we're
talking about ones

00:44:41.720 --> 00:44:44.830
where your goal is
commercial success,

00:44:44.830 --> 00:44:46.560
I think engaging
is core to that.

00:44:46.560 --> 00:44:49.130
You want you want
people to gravitate

00:44:49.130 --> 00:44:54.900
towards it, to play it, to not
drop it, and to get to the end.

00:44:54.900 --> 00:44:58.780
So to me, it doesn't feel like
compromising so much as, I

00:44:58.780 --> 00:45:00.170
think, it's just
one of the goals

00:45:00.170 --> 00:45:03.110
you have to hit as the project.

00:45:03.110 --> 00:45:07.610
Probably the thing that feels
like the most compromise

00:45:07.610 --> 00:45:11.370
is time and resources.

00:45:11.370 --> 00:45:15.710
So just having to
say, this doesn't

00:45:15.710 --> 00:45:20.910
feel like the best solution
but we have to move on.

00:45:20.910 --> 00:45:22.860
Everyone in games,
there's the phrase,

00:45:22.860 --> 00:45:26.220
you don't finish a
game, you abandon it.

00:45:26.220 --> 00:45:28.610
That's how it always
feels, no matter what.

00:45:36.187 --> 00:45:37.270
You want another question?

00:45:37.270 --> 00:45:38.300
Yeah.

00:45:38.300 --> 00:45:40.164
Yeah.

00:45:40.164 --> 00:45:43.230
AUDIENCE: The microphone
just comes to the area.

00:45:43.230 --> 00:45:46.464
I was wondering if you
had any recommendations

00:45:46.464 --> 00:45:51.695
for really good storytelling
games that you'd like to share.

00:45:51.695 --> 00:45:52.695
KELLEE SANTIAGO: Oh man.

00:45:55.410 --> 00:45:56.784
What's that?

00:45:56.784 --> 00:45:58.620
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:45:58.620 --> 00:46:01.122
KELLEE SANTIAGO: Yeah,
that would be good.

00:46:01.122 --> 00:46:04.260
Make a co-link-- Kellee's
favorite storytelling games.

00:46:06.860 --> 00:46:12.900
Probably two of the
ones in recent history

00:46:12.900 --> 00:46:21.610
would be "Papers,
please" and oh my gosh.

00:46:21.610 --> 00:46:23.270
Another one.

00:46:23.270 --> 00:46:27.180
"Papers, please,"
yeah, is one of them.

00:46:27.180 --> 00:46:30.942
Because it really
tells its story.

00:46:30.942 --> 00:46:33.400
It's one of those that tells
the story through every aspect

00:46:33.400 --> 00:46:36.060
of the game, the
visuals, the music,

00:46:36.060 --> 00:46:38.770
the narrative itself, and
then also the mechanics

00:46:38.770 --> 00:46:43.680
all place you in this
situation by which you're

00:46:43.680 --> 00:46:47.700
receiving the story
through all those elements.

00:46:47.700 --> 00:46:50.672
And it does it in a
really fantastic way.

00:46:54.731 --> 00:46:55.605
SAL YANEZ: Thank you.

00:46:58.400 --> 00:46:59.933
AUDIENCE: Do you
want another one?

00:46:59.933 --> 00:47:01.308
SAL YANEZ: You
can have one more.

00:47:08.822 --> 00:47:10.280
AUDIENCE: One of
my other questions

00:47:10.280 --> 00:47:14.127
is, how do you deal
with the internet?

00:47:14.127 --> 00:47:15.585
The dark underbelly
of the internet

00:47:15.585 --> 00:47:19.060
can be really toxic, especially
to [INAUDIBLE] game designers.

00:47:22.965 --> 00:47:25.739
Have you dealt with a lot of
vitriol from the internet?

00:47:25.739 --> 00:47:26.905
And how do you deal with it?

00:47:30.360 --> 00:47:32.240
KELLEE SANTIAGO: So I have not.

00:47:32.240 --> 00:47:35.090
I will say I'm not the most
outspoken social person

00:47:35.090 --> 00:47:37.550
on social media.

00:47:37.550 --> 00:47:41.180
And I think about that a lot.

00:47:41.180 --> 00:47:45.860
Am I not outspoken because I
don't want to deal with that?

00:47:45.860 --> 00:47:51.010
Is that a reason to not be
outspoken or vice versa?

00:47:51.010 --> 00:47:55.660
Or is it that I'm also
burnt on all social media

00:47:55.660 --> 00:47:58.730
platforms being designed to
sell you stuff right now?

00:47:58.730 --> 00:48:04.310
And that is just really
toxic in and of itself.

00:48:04.310 --> 00:48:08.670
That's a whole other
fireside chat maybe.

00:48:08.670 --> 00:48:12.280
But yeah, I am being
tracked somewhere.

00:48:12.280 --> 00:48:14.560
It's for my activities
in the games industry,

00:48:14.560 --> 00:48:18.510
because there's a whole idea
around the social justice

00:48:18.510 --> 00:48:20.160
warrior mafia.

00:48:20.160 --> 00:48:22.610
Which I love that that's
an insult of a name,

00:48:22.610 --> 00:48:26.320
because I think "social justice
warrior" sounds amazing.

00:48:26.320 --> 00:48:29.050
I would love that.

00:48:29.050 --> 00:48:31.420
But yeah, I haven't
experienced it.

00:48:31.420 --> 00:48:34.000
Certainly, many people
very close to me have it,

00:48:34.000 --> 00:48:37.200
and that's what I was
thinking about when

00:48:37.200 --> 00:48:41.130
I was thinking about the
separation between games

00:48:41.130 --> 00:48:44.060
and gaming culture.

00:48:44.060 --> 00:48:46.720
Specifically, my
professor, Tracy Fullerton,

00:48:46.720 --> 00:48:48.780
very recently went through this.

00:48:48.780 --> 00:48:51.240
And now she's just
not on Twitter

00:48:51.240 --> 00:48:52.370
and she's not on Facebook.

00:48:52.370 --> 00:48:57.130
She's just ghosted
herself from social media.

00:48:57.130 --> 00:48:59.390
And I don't know.

00:48:59.390 --> 00:49:08.600
That's a loss but she's
still doing her work.

00:49:08.600 --> 00:49:14.170
So yeah, I don't know how
we extract these things

00:49:14.170 --> 00:49:14.950
from each other.

00:49:18.640 --> 00:49:20.377
SAL YANEZ: Yes.

00:49:20.377 --> 00:49:20.960
AUDIENCE: Hey.

00:49:20.960 --> 00:49:24.210
So I was curious.

00:49:24.210 --> 00:49:28.500
Well, first I wanted to say
that when I was a little kid,

00:49:28.500 --> 00:49:30.244
Sierra Online put
out "King's Quest."

00:49:30.244 --> 00:49:31.160
KELLEE SANTIAGO: Yeah.

00:49:31.160 --> 00:49:33.720
AUDIENCE: And "King's Quest,"
one of the two creators of that

00:49:33.720 --> 00:49:34.900
was Roberta Williams.

00:49:34.900 --> 00:49:35.858
KELLEE SANTIAGO: Right.

00:49:35.858 --> 00:49:38.358
AUDIENCE: So it actually never
occurred to me until recently

00:49:38.358 --> 00:49:40.774
that women weren't actually a
part of the game development

00:49:40.774 --> 00:49:41.300
world.

00:49:41.300 --> 00:49:42.258
KELLEE SANTIAGO: Right.

00:49:42.258 --> 00:49:43.360
Yeah, right.

00:49:43.360 --> 00:49:45.780
AUDIENCE: Those were
also my favorite games.

00:49:45.780 --> 00:49:49.280
But what I wanted to ask
was, Sony gave you this time

00:49:49.280 --> 00:49:50.780
in order to develop this game.

00:49:50.780 --> 00:49:53.140
How much freedom
did they give you

00:49:53.140 --> 00:49:56.730
to just explore your own
thing versus reign you in

00:49:56.730 --> 00:50:00.760
and try to make a
commercially viable product?

00:50:00.760 --> 00:50:04.840
KELLEE SANTIAGO: So each game
that we did was more expensive.

00:50:04.840 --> 00:50:08.920
So on "Journey," it was really
interesting and educational

00:50:08.920 --> 00:50:11.010
for me, because we
had hit a budget

00:50:11.010 --> 00:50:13.030
point where suddenly
a lot more people were

00:50:13.030 --> 00:50:17.430
focused on the game.

00:50:17.430 --> 00:50:20.950
Again, their position towards
third party in general

00:50:20.950 --> 00:50:22.340
was pretty hands off.

00:50:22.340 --> 00:50:24.800
So I think we were
probably shielded

00:50:24.800 --> 00:50:27.720
from quite a lot of it.

00:50:27.720 --> 00:50:34.520
But before that, we were
operating at a budget

00:50:34.520 --> 00:50:36.392
which is a smart thing to do.

00:50:36.392 --> 00:50:37.850
When you're creating
content that's

00:50:37.850 --> 00:50:40.950
sort of weird and
different, or at least

00:50:40.950 --> 00:50:44.340
different from mainstream or
what's been done in the past,

00:50:44.340 --> 00:50:46.250
keeping your budget
low is a good way

00:50:46.250 --> 00:50:49.620
to just float under the radar.

00:50:49.620 --> 00:50:51.930
Because it won't require
that many approvals and not

00:50:51.930 --> 00:50:55.370
that many people have to
look at it to get paid.

00:50:55.370 --> 00:50:59.730
So yeah, it was very
educational in that way.

00:50:59.730 --> 00:51:04.600
But then getting to
"Journey," we got to see more,

00:51:04.600 --> 00:51:07.230
because now we need to charge
a certain price for it.

00:51:07.230 --> 00:51:09.271
So it really needs
to have these things.

00:51:09.271 --> 00:51:11.020
Now, by that point,
it was our third game,

00:51:11.020 --> 00:51:16.660
so our egos were pretty
high and that shielded us.

00:51:16.660 --> 00:51:21.110
For better or for worse, we
just didn't accept a lot.

00:51:26.302 --> 00:51:27.760
AUDIENCE: Hi, So
I really like when

00:51:27.760 --> 00:51:31.160
you were talking about games
being potentially an easier

00:51:31.160 --> 00:51:33.670
route into tech for people
from other backgrounds

00:51:33.670 --> 00:51:37.130
and also that you came from
theater yourself originally.

00:51:37.130 --> 00:51:41.140
Do you feel like there's not
that many easy ways for people

00:51:41.140 --> 00:51:43.640
from the arts to get
into tech, or it's

00:51:43.640 --> 00:51:47.045
been actually developing to be
a bit more easily accessible,

00:51:47.045 --> 00:51:47.920
or that it should be?

00:51:47.920 --> 00:51:50.185
Do you have any
thoughts about that?

00:51:50.185 --> 00:51:51.550
[INAUDIBLE]

00:51:51.550 --> 00:51:53.780
KELLEE SANTIAGO:
Yeah, so I'm not

00:51:53.780 --> 00:51:55.600
exposed to every sector
of tech, so there

00:51:55.600 --> 00:52:00.490
may be ones where it's
much easier than others.

00:52:03.185 --> 00:52:06.240
But for games, I
think fundamentally,

00:52:06.240 --> 00:52:07.970
for a lot of
technology companies,

00:52:07.970 --> 00:52:13.000
it's important to demonstrate
work on technology.

00:52:13.000 --> 00:52:17.840
So games now, there are so
many tools, and web development

00:52:17.840 --> 00:52:24.910
as well, to learn how to code.

00:52:24.910 --> 00:52:27.200
At the same time,
the specific coding

00:52:27.200 --> 00:52:32.690
that you learn for games,
that way of approaching it,

00:52:32.690 --> 00:52:34.670
I find just a really
useful practice

00:52:34.670 --> 00:52:35.670
in learning programming.

00:52:38.620 --> 00:52:46.080
Understanding 3D space is the
best way to learn 3D math.

00:52:46.080 --> 00:52:50.020
Approaching it in games was very
different than approaching it

00:52:50.020 --> 00:52:52.710
in just a textbook.

00:52:52.710 --> 00:52:56.850
So I think it's that practice
of doing and that you can do it,

00:52:56.850 --> 00:52:59.540
and also the reward of playing a
game that you made with someone

00:52:59.540 --> 00:53:01.740
else is a really great payoff.

00:53:01.740 --> 00:53:04.395
And so that creates
its own like, in a way,

00:53:04.395 --> 00:53:08.770
game loop and state
of flow through it.

00:53:08.770 --> 00:53:12.010
So fundamentally, you're
just practicing and getting

00:53:12.010 --> 00:53:15.650
that portfolio built
out, or at least

00:53:15.650 --> 00:53:19.677
a body of work you can reference
and take into an interview

00:53:19.677 --> 00:53:20.176
somewhere.

00:53:23.300 --> 00:53:25.690
Yeah, there was something
else I wanted to say about it,

00:53:25.690 --> 00:53:26.860
but I totally forget.

00:53:26.860 --> 00:53:28.151
You were asking something else?

00:53:29.597 --> 00:53:31.180
AUDIENCE: Is it easy
enough for people

00:53:31.180 --> 00:53:32.230
to find those opportunities?

00:53:32.230 --> 00:53:33.396
KELLEE SANTIAGO: Yeah, yeah.

00:53:33.396 --> 00:53:35.380
Oh yeah, so the other
part is, I think

00:53:35.380 --> 00:53:37.560
this is shifting
now slowly, which

00:53:37.560 --> 00:53:40.040
is really exciting to see.

00:53:40.040 --> 00:53:43.970
Well, there are definitely
more sectors now applying

00:53:43.970 --> 00:53:47.490
game design to their
work, like in politics,

00:53:47.490 --> 00:53:49.820
in health, in science.

00:53:49.820 --> 00:53:50.920
They're looking.

00:53:50.920 --> 00:53:53.200
Here at Google, there
have been more people

00:53:53.200 --> 00:53:55.520
from the game industry
hired in the last year

00:53:55.520 --> 00:53:56.680
than I think ever.

00:53:56.680 --> 00:53:59.615
And we're seeing that at many
other technology companies.

00:54:03.280 --> 00:54:07.390
So at the same time, people
with strict art backgrounds,

00:54:07.390 --> 00:54:11.240
I feel like there's still
this divide that I would like

00:54:11.240 --> 00:54:18.290
to keep bending us towards
having more creative directors

00:54:18.290 --> 00:54:23.380
and writers and people that
just have arts backgrounds.

00:54:23.380 --> 00:54:26.450
That's very valuable and
contributes something

00:54:26.450 --> 00:54:28.210
to all of our work.

00:54:28.210 --> 00:54:29.150
AUDIENCE: Thanks.

00:54:29.150 --> 00:54:32.110
KELLEE SANTIAGO: Yeah.

00:54:32.110 --> 00:54:32.942
SAL YANEZ: Yes?

00:54:32.942 --> 00:54:33.765
AUDIENCE: Um.

00:54:33.765 --> 00:54:35.265
SAL YANEZ: Just
with the microphone,

00:54:35.265 --> 00:54:38.384
please, because
there's a livestream.

00:54:38.384 --> 00:54:39.250
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:54:39.250 --> 00:54:43.030
So one of the many
pushbacks for Oculus

00:54:43.030 --> 00:54:44.406
has been the lack of content.

00:54:47.114 --> 00:54:50.650
A year in at Google, what
are we doing to address it?

00:54:50.650 --> 00:54:54.157
And how long do you think it
will be for good gaming content

00:54:54.157 --> 00:54:56.407
to show up on Daydream or
just for the virtual reality

00:54:56.407 --> 00:54:57.190
platform in general?

00:54:57.190 --> 00:54:59.773
KELLEE SANTIAGO: Yeah, , I mean,
certainly Daydream Publishing

00:54:59.773 --> 00:55:05.794
is trying to speed things
along and creating tools.

00:55:05.794 --> 00:55:07.460
I mean, there's also
the googly approach

00:55:07.460 --> 00:55:11.530
of creating easy to use
tools to make creating

00:55:11.530 --> 00:55:17.210
awesome experiences easier.

00:55:17.210 --> 00:55:24.390
The other part is the lower
cost of the hardware itself.

00:55:24.390 --> 00:55:28.200
So it being based on
smartphones, hopefully

00:55:28.200 --> 00:55:32.420
many people that subsidize
through their carriers,

00:55:32.420 --> 00:55:36.690
the viewer and controller
itself is at a low price point.

00:55:36.690 --> 00:55:41.700
And so that will allow more
people than other platforms

00:55:41.700 --> 00:55:42.960
to just have access.

00:55:42.960 --> 00:55:47.740
Because every phone is a
development kit as well.

00:55:47.740 --> 00:55:50.975
And so that'll just empower
a greater community.

00:55:50.975 --> 00:55:52.600
To me, that's always
what it comes down

00:55:52.600 --> 00:55:54.750
to is fundamentally that cost.

00:55:54.750 --> 00:55:57.554
I mean, that's
what we talk about.

00:55:57.554 --> 00:55:59.095
That was something
I learned at Ouya.

00:55:59.095 --> 00:56:01.510
And being more exposed to
the hardware side of things,

00:56:01.510 --> 00:56:04.310
it's really expensive
to import things

00:56:04.310 --> 00:56:07.020
to most South
American countries.

00:56:07.020 --> 00:56:13.900
So they don't even have
the hardware to work on.

00:56:13.900 --> 00:56:17.930
And then that's true within,
of course, certain populations

00:56:17.930 --> 00:56:19.260
in the United States as well.

00:56:19.260 --> 00:56:23.450
So the more we can do to
lower that barrier to entry,

00:56:23.450 --> 00:56:28.124
the more we enable more types
of people to express themselves.

00:56:28.124 --> 00:56:30.540
AUDIENCE: You're saying the
lower cost of hardware itself,

00:56:30.540 --> 00:56:33.684
not the cost of development
for a completely

00:56:33.684 --> 00:56:34.830
different platform?

00:56:34.830 --> 00:56:37.322
KELLEE SANTIAGO: Yeah,
I think that's a base.

00:56:41.250 --> 00:56:43.500
SAL YANEZ: So I want make
sure we do finish on time,

00:56:43.500 --> 00:56:44.990
because people have meetings.

00:56:44.990 --> 00:56:47.020
But I do want to
thank you very much,

00:56:47.020 --> 00:56:48.930
Kellee, for sharing your story.

00:56:48.930 --> 00:56:52.440
I think your story is very
powerful, very inspiring,

00:56:52.440 --> 00:56:54.290
especially for Hispanic
Heritage Month.

00:56:54.290 --> 00:56:57.320
It's full of finding
your inspiration,

00:56:57.320 --> 00:57:00.710
a sense of belonging,
building communities, bringing

00:57:00.710 --> 00:57:02.880
a passion that you have
into a new industry,

00:57:02.880 --> 00:57:05.920
and even changing paradigms,
looking at video games as art.

00:57:05.920 --> 00:57:07.545
So thank you very
much for sharing it.

00:57:07.545 --> 00:57:08.670
KELLEE SANTIAGO: Thank you.

00:57:08.670 --> 00:57:09.820
SAL YANEZ: Please, give
a big round of applause.

00:57:09.820 --> 00:57:10.944
KELLEE SANTIAGO: Thank you.

